      <div id="news" class="wide"> 
        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Does your area need a shell building?</h1>
          <span class="date">By Loren M. Matthes, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} August 18, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1lmatthes.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/lmatthes.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>Shell buildings are becoming more prevalent as the economy recovers. These &ldquo;business-ready&rdquo; nearly finished buildings may give your city, town or county a competitive edge in the economic development race when a site consultant is looking for a location &ndash; especially if the company they represent is on a fast track to be up and running. When the site consultant schedules a site visit, you have something (besides land) for them to see.</p>

<p>Shell buildings can usually be ready for occupancy 90 to 120 days after an agreement is reached, reducing project development time by as much as 75% and usually faster and less costly than renovating older facilities.</p>

<p>Most prospects for shell buildings are seeking easy highway access and a building that can be expanded. A location within a TIF district can provide an added bonus.</p>

<p>As an example, creating shell buildings has worked well to stimulate economic development for Delaware County, the City of Muncie and the Town of Daleville through public-private partnerships involving the Economic Development Alliance, county and local officials, the Delaware Advancement Corporation and private construction firms.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<table align="left" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="margin-right: 20px; width: 500px;">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td><img alt="" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/does-your-area-need-a-shell-building.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 362px;" /></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
			<p>Shell building constructed by Garmong Construction in Delaware County</p>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Roughly 70 to 80% of companies looking to expand are looking for available buildings,&rdquo; said Terry Murphy, vice president of economic development for the Muncie-Delaware County, Indiana Economic Development Alliance. If you don&rsquo;t have available buildings, you&rsquo;re not going to<br />
make the cut for places they visit.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Even when the shell building turned out not to be the right answer, the visits still produced a win for Delaware County when Keihn-Aircom North America decided to build an $80 million facility across the street and Diamond Plastics invested $8 million in a new building.</p>

<p>The Alliance has built seven occupied shell buildings that started at a total of 391,000 square feet. Those buildings have since expanded to 1.1 million square feet and brought 1,250 jobs to the area. The Alliance recently added two new shell buildings that could expand to another half million square feet of space.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Having a building available saves a company roughly nine months in construction and permitting time,&rdquo; Murphy adds. &ldquo;That can be a determining factor in their location decision.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Approximately 15 shell buildings have been built throughout the state and more are being planned.</p>

<p><b>What kind of a shell building is in demand?</b><br />
The Indiana Economic Development Corporation tracks what businesses are looking for and projects that a 50,000-square-foot building expandable to 200,000 square feet and with a 32-foot clear height will meet more than 50% of all market requests in Indiana.</p>

<p><b>How do you finance it?</b><br />
Most shell building projects are public-private partnerships between local governments and construction companies, which construct and help market the building. The local government (or a special entity) owns the building and secures the financing. Until the building is sold, the local government typically makes interest-only payments, often out of tax increment (TIF) revenue or Economic Development Income Tax (EDIT) revenue.</p>

<p><b>What if it doesn&rsquo;t sell? </b><br />
That&rsquo;s a potential downside. The local government is ultimately responsible if the building isn&rsquo;t sold within the planned three- to five-year timeframe. The short-term, interest-only loan will have to be replaced, and you&rsquo;ll be paying interest and principal for an empty building.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<table align="left" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="width: 500px; margin-right: 20px;">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td><img alt="" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/does-your-area-need-a-shell-building-2.jpg" style="width: 500px; height: 286px;" /></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>
			<p>Shell building constructed by Runnebohm Construction in Henry County</p>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Even if the shell building takes a few years to attract the right buyer, there can still be economic development benefits. Henry County has an available shell building that was completed in 2013.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Corey Murphy, CEO of the New Castle-Henry County Economic Development Corporation said, &ldquo;It (the shell building) is still doing its job. We wouldn&rsquo;t be getting visits or having conversations with prospects if we didn&rsquo;t have the product.&rdquo; He advises that shell buildings are not a guaranteed &ldquo;build it and they will come.&rdquo; Be prepared for a carrying cost. It must be viewed as a strategy to get looks. In 2014, Henry County attracted &ldquo;the look&rdquo; from prospect &ldquo;Boar&rsquo;s Head,&rdquo; which is now building its own $80 million, 150,000 square foot plant in the Henry County Industrial Park.</p>

<p><b>What are the dos and don&rsquo;ts?</b></p>

<p><b>Don&rsquo;t</b> build a shell building without consulting an independent financial advisor. If anyone says you don&rsquo;t need an outside financial opinion, be skeptical.</p>

<p><b>Do</b> start your project with a solid financial analysis: What are the financial risks? Can we find lower interest rates than the ones the builder arranges? Will we have sufficient income to make payments if it takes longer than expected to find buyers? How will our financial commitment to this project affect our ability to obtain other financing if another economic development opportunity crops up? Are there new or existing restrictions (example, outstanding bond covenants) that prevent us from using TIF revenue to make loan payments?</p>

<p><b>Do</b> consult legal counsel. As we advised above about seeing independent financial opinion, have an experienced legal team review the paperwork.</p>

<p>If you have questions about whether a shell building could stimulate economic development in your community, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_MSaJJKPdWU='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_MSaJJKPdWU'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>

