        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Statewide Look-The Real Numbers Behind Changes In Local Government Finance</h1>
          <span class="date">By Gerald G. Malone, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} August 18, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1gmalone.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/gmalone.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>Part 8 in a series &ndash; The effect on local governments</p>

<p>This series summarizes a study Umbaugh and Policy Analytics conducted for the Indiana Association of Cities and Towns to analyze trends over the past eight years regarding revenue and budgets for local governmental units and schools as Indiana has transitioned from 80% of Indiana local governments&rsquo; budgets being funded by property taxes in 2007 to the current level of 39%.</p>

<p>When the tax rate in your area is above the property tax caps, local governments reach a point where levying more in your tax rate doesn&rsquo;t result in collecting the full amount of the tax increase. The additional revenue to fund the levy increase either has to come from:</p>

<p>&bull; taxpayers still below the tax cap or<br />
&bull; other units of government.</p>

<p>Let&rsquo;s use the example of a coffee shop with an assessed value of $100,000. The municipality&rsquo;s total tax rate is $3.35. The coffee shop, which as a commercial property at the 3% tax cap, pays a maximum of $3,000 a year in property taxes.</p>

<p>Let&rsquo;s say the school district gets a levy increase of 20 cents.</p>

<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="width:620px">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td><img alt="" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/statewide-look-at-real-numbers.png" style="height:213px; width:235px" /></td>
			<td><img alt="" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/statewide-look-at-real-numbers-2.png" style="height:201px; width:234px" /></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>The coffee shop owner is OK with that, because she&rsquo;s still paying a maximum of $3,000.</p>

<p>The school gets more revenue, but still not the full amount of its levy. The additional revenue for the school district from the coffee shop&rsquo;s $3,000 tax payment is coming at the expense of the library, county, township and city.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="width:610px">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td><img alt="" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/statewide-look-at-real-numbers-3.png" style="height:304px; width:312px" /></td>
			<td><img alt="" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/statewide-look-at-real-numbers-4.png" style="height:292px; width:317px" /></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>

<p>Our analysis showed that if the City of Fort Wayne levied an additional dollar in property taxes, it would produce only 60 cents in revenue for the City &ndash; and 40 cents of that 60 would come out of distributions for other taxing units. The additional dollar in levy would generate just 20 cents of new revenue.</p>

<p>What can local governments do to meet growing expenses? We&rsquo;ll cover that in future installments of this series.</p>

<p>If you have questions about local government and school revenue and budgets, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_yTTxfeQTHt='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_yTTxfeQTHt'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>

