        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>How To Finance School Capital Maintenance Needs With Rolling Short-Term Debt</h1>
          <span class="date">By Belvia B. Gray, {if "CIPMA" != ""}CIPMA,{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} August 06, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1belvia.jpg" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/belvia.jpg"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>The stress on school districts&rsquo; Capital Projects Funds (CPF) has not let up. CPF dollars are not only being diminished by property tax caps, they are being tapped to cover certain salaries and utilities to relieve the pressure on the general fund. Capital needs, however, are not going away.</p>

<p>Establishing a rolling program of short-term debt is one way of handling HVAC repair and replacement, new roofs, carpeting, certain technology investments and other capital needs.</p>

<p>There are two approaches to establishing a rolling-debt program:</p>

<p>1) Look at your district&rsquo;s debt that will be paid off in the next few years. As these debts are paid off, you can replace them with new short-term debt with similar payments without increasing your debt service tax rate&mdash;or with a minimal increase.</p>

<p>2) If you do not have debt being paid off in the short term, the second approach is to make a conscious decision to increase tax rates, and carve out a new debt service amount you will devote to these types of projects. Finance your first capital maintenance bond for a short period, with the intent that new short-term debt will be issued each time an old one is paid off.</p>

<p>Having a cash flow projection prepared for tax rate management purposes is an excellent recommendation. This is especially important given the recent legislative change affecting the maximum operating balance allowable in the Debt Service Fund.</p>

<p>Certain recommendations apply regardless of which approach you choose:</p>

<p>&bull; Start by creating a system-wide plan for your capital needs, with estimated costs and identified sources of revenue to pay for them. This plan will guide your rolling-debt program and should be updated periodically.</p>

<p>&bull; The total estimated project costs must be less than $2 million per building, including hard and soft construction costs and the cost of bond issuance, to be considered a non-controlled project (and thus not subject to the petition-remonstrance process).</p>

<p>&bull; The short-term debt is often a General Obligation bond, but there are other options, depending on the scope of improvements needed.</p>

<p>&bull; Keep the term of the bonds short&mdash;preferably from one to five years. This allows you to add new projects when needed.</p>

<p>&bull; Issuing new debt can have tax cap ramifications for district revenue, so it&rsquo;s important to analyze all financial aspects before issuing new debt.</p>

<p>Interest rates are still low; however, rates are expected to continue to rise through the end of the year and thereafter. The good news is that bond buyers are still eager for these short-term investments, and recently we have seen interest rates in the 1% - 2% range with these types of financings.</p>

<p>If you have questions or need help establishing a rolling debt program to finance building improvements, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_enXRRijJsG='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_enXRRijJsG'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>

          <div id="tabs">
