        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>The Fed may be getting closer to raising interest rates</h1>
          <span class="date">By Jeffrey A. Messer, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "Director of Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC" != ""}Director of Umbaugh Cash Advisory Services, LLC,{/if} July 09, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1jmesser.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/jmesser.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>The Federal Reserve Open Market Committee met in June, and as expected, decided to keep the fed funds rate at its current 0.00% - 0.25% target range.</p>

<p>If, like me, you are frustrated earning so little interest on your funds, your wait might just about be over. As long as the unemployment rate continues to improve and inflation holds steady in the 2% range, the Fed stated that they would likely begin raising rates this year, perhaps as early as September.</p>

<p>However, there are a couple of factors that could cause the Fed to hold off on any rate increases, including:</p>

<p>1. Greece &ndash; As of the date of this article, Greece has failed to make a bailout loan payment to the International Monetary Fund (IMF). It has reached a point where the Greek government closed all banks this week and only allowed citizens to withdraw small amounts of money from their bank ATMs. The IMF has offered a new deal to the Greek government, but it contains austerity measures that they are not willing to accept. The Greek citizens voted in a referendum this week and decided not to take the offer from the IMF. Even if they refinance their loan, the country is in bad shape both financially and economically and may ultimately have to give up using the Euro as their currency and move back to the drachma. And while Greece makes up only a small portion of the European Union, investors and government officials are more worried about contagion, and fear that the same thing might happen to other weak EU countries such as Italy, Spain or Portugal.</p>

<p>2. U.S. Dollar - Recently the dollar has strengthened against other currencies. What that means is that U.S. goods sold abroad cost more and foreign made goods cost less. This could negatively impact demand for U.S. exports which could result in a slowdown in hiring in the U.S.</p>

<p>We have three months before the September Fed meeting. Hopefully by then the Greek situation will at least stabilize and not spill over into other countries. If all goes well, we still may be on track to see one or maybe even two increases in the fed funds rate before year end.</p>

<p>If you have questions about how changing interest rates impact your financial planning and investment strategy, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_MbNcRFayGT='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_MbNcRFayGT'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>

          <div id="tabs">
            <ul>
              <li id="first"><a href="#tabs-1">Give Article Feedback</a> &raquo;</li>
              <li>|</li>
              <li><a href="#tabs-2">E-mail Umbaugh</a> &raquo;</li>
              <li>|</li>
