        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Creative approach drives win-win for Tipton County and Chrysler</h1>
          <span class="date">By Matt Eckerle, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} June 19, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1MattEckerle.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/MattEckerle.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>“If you build it, they will come,” is a twist on the iconic phrase from the movie <i>Field of Dreams</i>. But what if your economic development doesn’t work out as planned?</p>

<p>It took patience and creativity, but Tipton County now has a happy ending for an economic development story that encountered challenges over the years.</p>

<p>The county issued bonds payable from project TIF revenues in 2008 for infrastructure improvements and land acquisition to support a new transmission plant being constructed for Getrag, a German company. The plant was to be owned and operated by Getrag to manufacture transmissions for Chrysler. The day after bonds were issued, Chrysler and Getrag’s alliance began to unravel. Getrag filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in November 2008, just as a global financial crisis unfolded. Lawsuits ensued.</p>

<p>What was supposed to be Tipton County’s largest economic development project, creating up to 1,400 jobs, was terminated, leaving Tipton County with an empty factory the size of 16 football fields and no new jobs in sight.</p>

<p>A new prospect emerged in 2010 when Abound Solar purchased the building, intending to develop a facility for manufacturing solar panels, but that company also filed for bankruptcy before the facility could be completed.</p>

<p>The building now has come full circle. With the American automobile industry rebounding, Chrysler approached Tipton County in 2012 about its desire to purchase the vacant building, finish it and operate a new state-of-the-art transmission assembly plant. Chrysler requested real and personal property tax abatement for its new investment.</p>

<p>As they contemplated that request, Tipton County officials wanted a viable occupant for the high-profile facility located at the intersection of US 31 and State Road 28, but the county also had financial obligations for the 2008 bonds issued for the original project and a 2010 bond associated with the Abound Solar project. Those obligations were secured by TIF revenues generated by the facility.</p>

<p>Both sides came together to explore what each of them needed to make the new venture feasible. They then evaluated a variety of traditional and alternative abatement structures.</p>

<p>At the end of these conversations, both sides got what they needed.</p>
<ul>
    <li>Tipton County did not grant any abatement for the existing building or the proposed real property improvements, because of the need to preserve TIF revenue to make payments on the outstanding bonds.</li>
    <li>Both sides agreed to a modified 10-year abatement of taxes on personal property that began at 42% in year one and ended at 6% in year 10. The modified abatement schedule provided Chrysler with the financial incentive it needed and Tipton County with additional TIF revenues to accelerate repayment of its 2010 bonds.</li>
</ul>

<p>As with any well-constructed TIF project, it comes down to considering all factors, including the number and pay level of jobs being created, the value received by both parties, the useful life of buildings and equipment, and the impact on existing and proposed TIF obligations. Occasionally a creative approach is required to achieve the goals of all parties involved in an economic development project.</p>

<p>The plant opened in 2014 and expects to employ 850 workers when fully in operation, building fuel-efficient nine-speed automatic transmissions for Dodge and Jeep vehicles.</p>

<p>There were pauses along the way, but they built it, and jobs did come.</p>

<p><i>If you have questions about TIF, Tax Abatement or the new Super Abatements, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_NDSkleSVZp='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_NDSkleSVZp'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</i></p>
          <div id="tabs">
