        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Annexation Impacted by New Law</h1>
          <span class="date">By Deen C. Rogers, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} June 10, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1drodgers.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/drodgers.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>As we anticipated in the <a data-cke-saved-href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/will-annexation-laws-change" href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/will-annexation-laws-change">February issue</a> of Vision, some recommendations about annexation from last year’s Interim Study Committee on Government were included in a bill passed in the 2015 legislative session.</p>

<p>SEA 330 makes annexation more difficult for cities and towns. Annexations initiated by municipalities are still possible, but they will take more time and perhaps cost more.</p>

<p>Here are the highlights of what the new law does:<br>
<br>
•It requires six months of upfront community outreach to inform citizens about the annexation before an annexation ordinance is adopted.</p>

<p>•Your fiscal plan will need more detailed information.</p>

<p>•It will now take just 51% of landowner signatures (or 60% of assessed value) for a remonstrance to go to court, instead of the current 65%.</p>

<p>•If at least 65% of landowners sign a remonstrance petition (or 80% assessed value), it stops the annexation, without the court being involved.</p>

<p>•An Economic Development Protection Provision (which does not take effect until 2017) allows an annexation involving an economic development project to go to the courts, even if 65% of landowners sign a remonstrance petition. There are many technical requirements to meet this provision, but it will be important to know them in advance if you anticipate needing this option.</p>

<p>•Municipalities must provide a place where remonstrance petitions can be signed.</p>

<p>•Remonstrance petitions will now be filed with the county auditor instead of the courts.</p>

<p>•In a remonstrance hearing, courts will be prohibited from considering personal finances or business finances of a land owner or resident as a factor for determining whether the annexation will have a significant financial impact.</p>

<p>•Once a remonstrance petition is filed, the fiscal plan can’t be amended without consent of 65% of the remonstrators.</p>

<p>•If remonstrators prevail, they may recover reasonable attorney’s fees from the municipality up to $37,500.</p>

<p>•It extends the agricultural exemption to all annexations, so farmers do not pay municipal taxes if their annexed property is classified agricultural for property tax purposes.</p>

<p>•Remonstrance waivers, which did not previously have a statutory limit, will be limited to 15 years going forward; municipalities with existing remonstrance waivers with a deed recorded after June 30, 2015 must provide written notice to property owners that the waiver exists.</p>

<p>•Municipalities may be required to assume county debt or make payments to the county in certain circumstances.</p>

<p>Annexation is often an emotional issue. Having a solid plan for using the six months of community outreach well – to both explain the need for the annexation and listen to citizen concerns – should help avoid a remonstrance.</p>

<p>If you have questions or need help with an annexation, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_yZNEqDkvcJ='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_yZNEqDkvcJ'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>. Deen Rogers will be a presenter at the July 22 IACT workshop: Growing Your Community – An Overview of Indiana’s Annexation Laws.</p>
