        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>The Mechanics of Property Tax Abatement Part 2</h1>
          <span class="date">By Matt Eckerle, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} June 10, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1MattEckerle.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/MattEckerle.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>In recent issues of Vision, we’ve talked about Tax Increment Financing (TIF) and property tax abatement as financial tools for your “toolbox” of local incentives to make your community a more desirable location in the eyes of new or growing companies. (If you missed the <a data-cke-saved-href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/property-tax-abatement-another-economic-development-tool1" href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/property-tax-abatement-another-economic-development-tool1">first</a>, <a data-cke-saved-href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/Property-Tax-Abatement-Another-Economic-Development-Tool-Part-2-in-the-s" href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/Property-Tax-Abatement-Another-Economic-Development-Tool-Part-2-in-the-s">second</a> and <a data-cke-saved-href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/the-mechanics-of-property-tax-abatement" href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/the-mechanics-of-property-tax-abatement">third</a> installments, click to read them.)</p>

<p><b>Abatement Mechanics</b></p>

<p>When considering a new abatement on personal property owned by a company that has existing personal property within the taxing district, it is prudent to analyze the possible impact of the Minimum Value Ratio (MVR) on the taxable value of the existing and new personal property. The MVR is applied to the calculation of personal property abated assessed value when the total book value of personal property is less than the 30% depreciation floor. If the true tax value of existing equipment has reached the 30% depreciation floor, it is possible for the value of an abatement on new personal property to exceed the actual book value of the new personal property being abated. This calculation can have the effect of spreading the benefit of abated assessed value to existing personal property value that is not part of the abatement granted to the new equipment.</p>

<p>Since designating bodies have some flexibility to determine the term and percentages of property tax abatements, it is possible to structure a new personal property abatement to minimize the possible impact of the MVR on existing personal property assessed value. Analyzing the existing and new personal property and the impact of the MVR on the new personal property tax abatement will help you determine if an alternative abatement schedule is appropriate.</p>

<p>In a sample scenario, a company’s existing personal property investment is $100 million has been depreciated to its lowest level and is now valued at the 30% depreciation floor or $30 million, which will hold constant over the next 10 years if there is no new investment. However, if the company invests $10 million in new equipment, the assessed value of new and existing equipment will climb to $33 million. Because of the application of the MVR in the abatement calculation, traditional personal property tax abatement percentages applied to the new personal property would cause the abated assessed value for the new personal property to exceed its book value for the first five years.</p>

<p><img data-cke-saved-src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/umbaugh-tax-chart.jpg" src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/umbaugh-tax-chart.jpg" alt=""></p>

<p>By utilizing modified abatement schedules, it is possible to keep the abated assessed value at or below the book value of the new personal property, thus preserving the assessed value of the existing personal property, while still providing value to the taxpayer.</p>

<p>The modified personal property tax abatement limits the increase in the company’s personal property tax bill as the new personal property is added, yet still builds new taxable assessed value to benefit all taxing units.</p>

<p>In our next issue, we’ll share another story about how a creative approach to incentives created a win-win for the company and an entire county.</p>

<p>If you have questions about TIF, Tax Abatement or the new Super Abatements, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_PSCxQWnBwF='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_PSCxQWnBwF'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
