        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>The 2015 Legislative Changes that Matter Most to Local Governments</h1>
          <span class="date">By Daniel A. Hedden, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} June 03, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1dhedden.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/dhedden.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>Nearly half of the bills and joint resolutions passed in the 2015 session of the Indiana General Assembly had some effect on local governments. We don’t have room to cover them all in detail, but this is a brief summary of the ones with the greatest impact on local government finance:</p>

<p><b>The “dark store” fix</b> – SEA 436 is important to local governments and schools throughout the state. It addresses the “dark store” issue created by the Meijer and Kohl’s tax court cases, which allowed the assessed value of big box stores to be reduced if they were near other empty retail buildings. Without this fix, local governments were at risk of losing an estimated $3.5 billion in assessed value.</p>

<p><b>Annexation</b>—SEA 330 places additional limits on municipalities’ ability to annex. (We’ll have more on this in a future Vision article.)</p>

<p><b>Business personal property tax</b>—SEA 436 eliminated business personal property tax for businesses with less than $20,000 of business personal property (BPP), but HEA1472 allows a county council to impose a $50 flat fee to taxpayers who quality for the BPP exemption.</p>

<p><b>Audit fees</b>—State Board of Accounts (SBOA) audit fees increase from $45/day to $175/day as part of the budget bill.</p>

<p><b>SBOA audits</b>—HEA 1104 allows a “risk and needs-based” system to determine the frequency of SBOA audits. Annual audits will be needed for units that issue bonds, receive federal grants or have continuing disclosure requirements.</p>

<p><b>Internal controls/GAAP</b> – HEA 1264 created new requirements for internal control policies and training. A section of this law (to be implemented in phases) prohibits political subdivisions from issuing bonds if they have not filed required annual financial reports with the SBOA using Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) accounting and reporting.</p>

<p><b>CAGIT, COIT and CEDIT</b> – HEA 1485 provides for a transition over the next two years of county adjusted gross income tax, county option income tax, county economic development taxes and various local special purpose income taxes to a single local income tax with three rate components. We’ll cover this in more detail in a future Vision issue.</p>

<p><b>Local food and beverage taxes</b> - HEA 1044 authorizes food and beverage taxes for two specific communities. More importantly, it urges creating a committee to study whether it is more effective to have a uniform tax that local governments could adopt without requiring future legislative action.</p>

<p><b>Redevelopment Commissions/TIF reporting</b> - SEA 567 consolidates reporting requirements for redevelopment commissions and sets up new policies for TIF fund disbursements.</p>

<p><b>Indiana Regional City Fund</b> - HEA 1403 establishes the Indiana regional city fund to provide grants and loans to regional development authorities. This fund will be administered by the Indiana Economic Development Corporation (IEDC).</p>

<p><b>Tax amnesty</b> - The budget bill requires the Department of Revenue to establish a tax amnesty program using the first $84 million deposited into the Indiana Regional Cities Development Fund.</p>

<p><b>Public Safety Answer Points</b> - HEA1475 and the budget bill made changes for PSAPs, which is covered elsewhere in this issue.</p>

<p><b>Property tax appeals fund</b> - HEA 1603 allows a taxing unit’s fiscal officer to establish a property tax appeals fund, sets requirements for how that money may be used and requires the county assessor to send a quarterly notification to the fiscal officer of each taxing unit affected by a property tax appeal.</p>

<p><b>Broadband Ready Communities</b> - HB 1101 establishes within IEDC a Broadband Ready Communities Development Center. Local governments may opt in to this program.</p>

<p>In addition to future articles about the annexation and tax consolidation legislative changes, we’ll also update you soon on how legislative changes affected schools.</p>

<p>If you have questions about how legislative changes will affect your local governmental unit, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_GUXTEKPOWc='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_GUXTEKPOWc'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script></p>
