        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>HB 1475 Provides Funding Opportunity for Public Safety</h1>
          <span class="date">By Paige E. Sansone, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} June 03, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1pgregory.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/pgregory.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>Recent legislation passed in HEA 1475 makes it easier to adopt the Public Safety Local Option Income Tax (LOIT). The bill removes the requirement that a county must impose other forms of taxes before adopting the Public Safety LOIT. The bill also provides that in a county in which the Public Safety LOIT is not in effect on July 1, 2015, the adopting body may dedicate 100% of the revenue derived from the tax to the funding of a Public Safety Answering Point (PSAP), commonly known as an E911 dispatch center. In addition to dispatch services, a Public Safety LOIT may be used for a wide variety of public safety services related to police, fire, emergency ambulance services, probation programs, community corrections, juvenile detention, county jails and environmental clean-up. Unless the tax is dedicated 100% to dispatch, the Public Safety LOIT is distributed to the county unit and all municipalities within the county. Townships may apply to the county unit to receive a portion of the Public Safety LOIT; however, if approved by the county the distributive shares to the county and municipal units will be reduced accordingly.</p>

<p>The maximum rate allowed for Public Safety LOIT is .25%. The appropriate adopting body of the tax depends on whether a county currently has CAGIT (County Adjusted Gross Income Tax), COIT (County Option Income Tax) or only CEDIT (County Economic Development Income Tax). The tax may be enacted by the County Council in CAGIT counties and the County Income Tax Council in COIT counties. If your county has CEDIT only, the Public Safety LOIT may be enacted by the same body that adopted the CEDIT (either the County Council or the County Income Tax Council, whichever acted first). For the tax to be effective January 1, 2016, an ordinance must be adopted no later than October 31, 2015.</p>

<p>If you have any questions about Public Safety LOIT or need assistance, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_WEzpalCHlh='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_WEzpalCHlh'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
