        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Utility Legislation Updates</h1>
          <span class="date">By Scott A. Miller, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Partner" != ""}Partner,{/if} June 03, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1smiller.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/smiller.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>A sometimes raucous 2015 legislative session wrapped up a few weeks ago. While the dust has yet to settle on some topics, several bills were passed that will impact the utility sector.</p>

<p>HEA 1319 as adopted merged two separate topics:</p>

<p>• First, it provides that under certain circumstances a public water or wastewater utility that acquires a distressed utility may petition the Indiana Utility Regulatory Commission (IURC) to include in its rate base the cost differential of the acquisition price and the historical cost of the distressed utility minus contributions or advances in aid of construction plus applicable accrued depreciation.</p>

<p>• Second, it requires the Department of Natural Resources to cooperate with the U.S. Geological Survey to establish a program allowing volunteers to monitor ground and surface water resources and provide data to the Natural Resources Commission as it continues its assessment of the availability of water resources throughout the state.</p>

<p>SEA 177 and SEA 516 are companion bills that modify the Distribution System Improvement Charges (DSIC) that can be approved by the IURC. The DSIC is a mechanism for utilities to recover certain costs associated with distribution system improvements outside of a normal rate case proceeding before the IURC. The bills increase the allowed rate adjustment from 5% to 10% of base revenue approved in the utility’s last rate case and authorize municipal and not-for-profit utilities to seek a DSIC.</p>

<p>SEA 309 provides that after May 19, 2015, a municipality that owns and operates an electric utility and annexes an area beyond its assigned utility service territory may not petition the IURC to change the assigned service area of the municipality to include the annexed area as permitted under prior law, except by mutual agreement of the affected electricity suppliers and approval of the IURC.</p>

<p>SEA 474 requires the Indiana Finance Authority (IFA) to prepare an analysis of the planning and long-range needs of water utilities serving the 15 most populous cities in Indiana plus five other utilities selected by the IFA that serve less than 10,000 customers. The IFA is to submit this analysis to the legislative council by November 1, 2015.</p>

<p>If you have questions about how legislation changes impact your utility, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_sTNlIXdKtD='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_sTNlIXdKtD'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
