        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Property Tax Abatement: Another Economic Development Tool - Part 2 in the series</h1>
          <span class="date">By Matt Eckerle, {if "" != ""},{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} April 29, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1MattEckerle.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/MattEckerle.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>In past issues of Vision, we talked about Tax Increment Financing (TIF) as <a data-cke-saved-href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/tif-flexibility-can-benefit-schools-and-other-taxing-units" href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/tif-flexibility-can-benefit-schools-and-other-taxing-units">one financial tool </a>to help communities compete for economic development projects to grow their tax base and bring jobs to the community and the advantages and disadvantages of property tax abatement, <a data-cke-saved-href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/property-tax-abatement-another-economic-development-tool1" href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/property-tax-abatement-another-economic-development-tool1">another financial tool</a> for your “toolbox” of local incentives to make your community a more desirable location in the eyes of new or growing companies.</p>

<p>In basic terms, a property tax abatement is a phasing in of property taxes over a defined period of time for new real property improvements, new buildings and new equipment (personal property).</p>

<p><b>What is eligible for property tax abatement? </b><br>
• New buildings (non-retail, non-residential)<br>
• Improvements to existing buildings (non-retail, non-residential)<br>
• New equipment for manufacturing, logistical distribution, information technology, research and development<b> (must be new to Indiana)</b><br>
• Certain eligible vacant buildings</p>

<p>Land and an entire list of property types defined in statute are<b> not</b> eligible for property tax abatements.</p>

<p><b>How long is a property tax abatement?</b><br>
• “Up to 10 years” is the most common term, with the local government’s fiscal body having the flexibility to set the number of years and the applicable percentages for each year.<br>
• Three-year property tax abatements for existing assessed value are possible on large vacant buildings that meet certain requirements<br>
• Five-year property tax abatements all allowed in residentially distressed areas<br>
• 20-Year “Super” abatements are allowed on depreciable personal property. This is a new option becoming available July 1, 2015. (More on this later.)</p>

<p><b>Develop a property tax abatement policy</b>—It’s a good idea for your government body to develop a policy about how you will evaluate projects for property tax abatement eligibility. Criteria may include the economic impact of the project, the amount of investment, the number of jobs or the wage level. Policies may be structured to encourage certain types of development, or to evaluate each project on its individual merits. It is important to be able to justify why you grant various levels of property tax abatement. Companies considering your community and existing companies within your community will take note of incentives granted, and having well-defined incentive policies can help you explain the justification behind granting those incentives.</p>

<p><b>Plan for annual compliance</b> —The company receiving a property tax abatement is required to file a form each year showing that it is complying with the Statement of Benefits form that is filed as part of an abatement request. The compliance form tracks a company’s actual investment, employment and wages versus what had been estimated in the original property tax abatement request. The designating entity has the opportunity to review this compliance form to determine whether or not to grant the approved property tax abatement for the given year.<br>
<br>
In our next issues, we’ll cover more technical details about property tax abatements.</p>

<p>If you have questions about TIF, Tax Abatement or the new Super Abatements, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_vhNtYoTlVg='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_vhNtYoTlVg'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
