        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Are you sick of potholes? I am.</h1>
          <span class="date">By Heidi L. Amspaugh, {if "CIPMA" != ""}CIPMA,{/if} {if "Manager" != ""}Manager,{/if} April 15, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1hAmspaugh.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/hAmspaugh.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>Swerving back and forth, back and forth, do you think you&rsquo;re watching your son or daughter play a video game? No, you&rsquo;re driving down the street after a long, snowy winter trying to avoid the craters in the ground, otherwise known as potholes.</p>

<p>Questions arise this time of year about how local governments plan to fund and fill the potholes on local roads and streets. One funding option available, if you haven&rsquo;t already implemented it, is the County Wheel Tax and Excise Surtax. Fifty Indiana counties have adopted them.</p>

<p>County Councils or County Income Tax Councils have the option to adopt an ordinance to impose a County Wheel Tax and County Motor Vehicle Excise Surtax. Both the Wheel Tax and Excise Surtax must be implemented simultaneously. If you adopt them before June 30, they become effective the following January 1. Now is the time to act for next year&rsquo;s pothole season!</p>

<p>The Wheel Tax is imposed on larger vehicles, such as buses, RVs, semi-trailers, tractors and trucks; the Excise Surtax is imposed on passenger vehicles, motorcycles and other small vehicles. Indiana statute details the ranges of tax and sets limitations for various vehicle categories. The County Council decides the rates &ndash; within the statutory limitations&mdash;for each type of vehicle. The taxes are then imposed and collected through the Bureau of Motor Vehicles (BMV) and remitted monthly to the county treasurer.</p>

<p>Once the taxes are collected, the tax revenue is distributed monthly by the county auditor to the county, cities and towns based upon the percentage of population and the percentage of street mileage in the county, similar to the Motor Vehicle Highway (MVH) distribution of taxes. The county, cities and towns may use Wheel Tax and Excise Surtax revenues to construct, reconstruct, repair or maintain streets and roads within their jurisdictions.</p>

<p>If you have questions about adopting a Wheel Tax and Excise Surtax or need assistance calculating the amount of revenue they could generate, please contact us at <a href="mailto:vision@umbaugh.com"><ins><span data-eeEncEmail_eeikbeZkln='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_eeikbeZkln'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script></ins></a>.</p>

