        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Need Ideas to Bridge Funding Gaps?</h1>
          <span class="date">By Paige E. Sansone, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} March 03, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1pgregory.png" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/pgregory.png"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>As you start the year with a new budget, you are probably like many other taxing units in the State. Resources are not enough to cover increasing costs and bridging funding gaps is becoming more and more difficult. We have a few ideas for your consideration.</p>

<p>1) <i>Reestablish the CCD Fund Tax Rate</i><br />
It may be time to reestablish the rate on your Cumulative Capital Development (&ldquo;CCD&rdquo;) Fund. If you have a CCD Fund, you may have noticed the rate declining over the past few years. This may be related to reassessment and annual trending. Reestablishing to the maximum rate may provide your community with additional property tax dollars to fund much needed projects or equipment. Municipalities may use the CCD Fund for operating costs in addition to capital projects. The deadline to complete the statutory process to reestablish cumulative fund rates is August 1. It is best to start that process sooner rather than later. The maximum CCD Fund rates are as follows:</p>

<p><ins>Municipalities</ins><br />
$.05 - in counties that have adopted CAGIT or COIT<br />
$.04 &ndash; in counties without CAGIT or COIT<br />
<br />
<ins>Counties</ins><br />
$.0333 &ndash; in counties that have adopted CAGIT or COIT<br />
$.0233 &ndash; in counties without CAGIT or COIT</p>

<p>2) <i> Establish Stormwater Fees</i><br />
Another idea to consider is storm water fees. You wouldn&rsquo;t think of operating a municipal water utility without charging for the water. And although they may complain about them, customers are now accustomed to being billed a separate user fee to handle sanitary wastewater treatment. Initiating a charge for handling stormwater may be next. It is part of the trend to identify the services local governments provide to residents and businesses and recapture the actual costs of providing each service. Stormwater fees may be set to recover the costs of constructing, maintaining, operating and equipping stormwater improvements. If these items are currently funded from a property tax supported fund (like General), stormwater fees could free up funds for other budget expenditures such as police or fire. To date, at least 60 communities have established stormwater user fees.</p>

<p>3) <i>Public Safety LOIT</i><br />
Public Safety is one of the most expensive services provided by local government and unfortunately is not immune to budgetary constraints. All counties have the option of generating additional revenue by adopting a Public Safety Local Option Income Tax (&ldquo;LOIT&rdquo;). (The tax must be adopted with either the Levy Freeze LOIT or the Property Tax Relief LOIT.) Revenue collected from Public Safety LOIT is distributed to County and Municipal units and may be used for just about anything related to public safety including police, fire, emergency medical services, probation programs, community corrections, and pension payment to public safety personnel.</p>

<p>4) <i>Payment in Lieu of Taxes and Hydrant Rental</i><br />
The city&rsquo;s municipal utilities can also provide assistance. For example the city could charge the municipal utilities for payment in lieu of property taxes in recognition that the city would have received property taxes on the utility plant had it been privately owned. Municipal hydrant rental can be converted to a monthly user charge applicable to water customers eliminating the need to fund this item through property taxes.</p>

<p>If you have any questions about the above the revenue options mentioned above or need assistance, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_pWcohqxlbU='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_pWcohqxlbU'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>

