        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>What Your Library Should Consider Before Issuing Bonds</h1>
          <span class="date">By Belvia B. Gray, {if "CIPMA" != ""}CIPMA,{/if} {if "Principal" != ""}Principal,{/if} February 17, 2015</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1belvia.jpg" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/belvia.jpg"/></div>
          {/if}
          <p>To state the obvious, public libraries are public buildings. They get a lot of wear and tear as people use the facility day in and day out – which is a positive sign your library is a valuable resource for your community. Similarly, libraries need to update technology and replace roofs and mechanical systems as your building (or buildings) age. Somewhere in your long-range plan, you probably have included facility improvements, and that takes money. </p>

<p>  Before you make plans to issue bonds, make sure you’ve done your homework.</p><ol>
    <li>Assess your facilities. You may want to engage an architect to perform a formal facility assessment, particularly if it involves building infrastructure. You can perform your own informal assessment of worn carpets, aging computers, technology infrastructure and other items that should be replaced on a periodic basis. Many libraries find it helpful to develop a running list and set high, medium and low priorities. If your maintenance funds are limited (and aren’t they always?), you’ll know what to attack first.</li>
    <li>Attach a price tag to your facility needs. You will probably need to engage outside professionals to establish a reliable estimate. You may be able to pay for some items out of your annual capital budget; others may require outside funding.</li>
    <li>Look at your existing indebtedness and when it will be fully repaid. If you have existing bonds that will be paid off in the near future, you may be able to schedule the issuance of new bonds to coincide with when other debt rolls off, minimizing the tax impact.</li>
    <li>Get professionals involved. Before you issue new debt, you’ll need to evaluate the impact to taxpayers and the impact of tax caps on local property taxes as well as confirm the timeline for all the required steps for approving debt and issuing bonds.</li>
    <li>Be in touch with your authorizing body. You will need their approval to issue debt, so you want to talk to the members of the authorizing body early and often about what you are considering. You want your project to be fully vetted, so it doesn’t come as a surprise when you ask them to approve your request.</li>
</ol>

<p>  In a previous issue of Vision, we described the advantages of establishing a rolling program of short-term debt as a way of handling HVAC repair and replacement, new roofs, carpeting, certain technology investments and other capital needs. If you want to consider a long-term rolling program, you can read about it <a href="http://www.umbaugh.com/latest-news/finance-school-capital-maintenance-needs-with-rolling-short-term-debt">here</a>.</p>

<p>  If you have questions or need help developing a financial plan for library improvements, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_aOIacKhTDL='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_aOIacKhTDL'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
	  
          <div id="tabs">
            <ul>
              <li id="first"><a href="#tabs-1">Give Article Feedback</a> &raquo;</li>
              <li>|</li>
              <li><a href="#tabs-2">E-mail Umbaugh</a> &raquo;</li>
              <li>|</li>
              <li>
                <FORM>
                  <INPUT TYPE="button" value="Print Article" onClick="window.print()" class="articleBtn">
                </FORM>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <div id="tabs-1" class="tab_content" style="display: none;">
              <h2>Send your feedback:</h2>
              <div class="contact">
                                                <form id="feedback" action="what-your-library-should-consider-before-issuing-bonds" method="post" name="feedback">
                  <div style="float:left; width:318px;">
                    <div class="formblock">
                      <label class="screen-reader-text">Is this item worthy of implementation?</label>
                      <input type="radio" name="feedback1" value="Yes">
                      Yes
                      <input type="radio" name="feedback1" value="No">
                      No
                      <input type="radio" name="feedback1" value="Maybe">
                      Maybe <br />
                    </div>
