        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>Is Water a Scarce Indiana Resource?</h1>
          <span class="date">By Christina De Witt, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Manager" != ""}Manager,{/if} November 26, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1De_Witt.jpg" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/De_Witt.jpg"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>It’s easy to take safe and reliable drinking water for granted. We are accustomed to turning on the faucet and not even thinking about the water that flows from it. Drought conditions during the summer of 2012 that caused water use restrictions in portions of the state led many to consider the importance of ensuring the long-term supply of one of our most precious resources.</p>

<p>The Indiana Chamber of Commerce coordinated an in-depth study of water resources as part of its Indiana Vision 2025. The water resource report’s three most critical goals were: determine how much water Indiana has, estimate how much water the state will need in the future and identify what it will take to meet the needs of expected growth. This article highlights the findings and recommendations of the Chamber’s report, Water and Economic Development in Indiana; Modernizing the State’s Approach to a Critical Resource, issued in August 2014.</p>

<p>Findings:<br>
• Indiana has abundant water resources, but ranks number one in the country for the percentage of the economy that depends on water, due to the growing medical and pharmaceutical industries, manufacturing and irrigation.<br>
• Water is critical to economic growth and sustainability. Increased demand will require more formal and technical methods to meet water needs and statewide capital investment in infrastructure plans.<br>
• Water supply in Indiana varies by region. The supply north of the Wabash River is relatively abundant, but has experienced greater demand recently for seasonal irrigation especially for agriculture. Monitoring the seasonal rebound of aquifers after summer pumping requires additional data collection.<br>
• Central Indiana’s available water supply is marginal, which could pose a risk to long-term economic growth. Future demand is expected to increase 50 million gallons per day by 2050. To meet seasonal peak demands, Central Indiana will need to consider more surface water storage, well fields in other watersheds, conservation and demand management.<br>
• Regions south of Indianapolis need a more diversified water supply; local water sources are not expected to meet future needs.</p>

<p>Recommendations:<br>
• Begin public outreach to create awareness about the need for water supply planning that includes the public and high-capacity water users.<br>
• Establish and implement a water conservation plan to reduce the need for infrastructure capacity projects.<br>
• Define areas of the state that rely on the same watershed so they can coordinate and plan for water supply demands.<br>
• Fund research for engineering and policy developments to implement a long-term water resource plan.</p>

<p>If you have questions about how planning for adequate water resources affects your local government’s plans for infrastructure or economic development or if you would like a copy of the water report, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_ODiUIYPBpV='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_ODiUIYPBpV'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>
