        <div class="news-story last pxBuffer">
          <h1>WIFIA: A New Source for Funding Water Infrastructure Projects</h1>
          <span class="date">By Christina De Witt, {if "CPA" != ""}CPA,{/if} {if "Manager" != ""}Manager,{/if} September 03, 2014</span><br />
          {if "filedir_1De_Witt.jpg" != ""}
          <div class="alignright"><img src="http://www.umbaugh.com/uploads/De_Witt.jpg"/></div>
          {/if}
          
	  <p>​Many utilities are looking for ways to fund water infrastructure projects. The federal government is working on a program to increase and assist with funding water infrastructure projects in the form of the Water Infrastructure Finance and Innovation Act (WIFIA). Specific details are still being spelled out for the federal plan, but we can share initial details.</p>

<p>The U.S. Congress enacted water resource legislation on June 10, 2014 to establish WIFIA as a five-year pilot program. WIFIA is being modeled on the Transportation Infrastructure Finance and Innovation Act (TIFIA) of 1998 that provided federal assistance for over $16 billion for transportation projects. WIFIA will provide a funding mechanism for water-related infrastructure projects beyond the current capacity of State Revolving Fund (SRF) programs.</p>

<p>&bull; Eligible recipients range from municipal entities to State Revolving Fund programs</p>

<p>&bull; To be considered an eligible project, the borrower must be deemed credit worthy, requiring a rating opinion on outstanding obligations.</p>

<p>&bull; Projects must be reasonably anticipated to cost no less than $20 million &ndash; or $5 million for small community projects of less than 25,000 residents.</p>

<p>&bull; The maximum amount of the loan cannot exceed 49% of the eligible project costs and the total federal assistance cannot exceed 80% of the total project costs.</p>

<p>&bull; Tax-exempt financing cannot be used to pay the non-federal share of the project cost.</p>

<p>&bull; Projects must have a dedicated source of revenue to be pledged to the repayment.</p>

<p>&bull; Davis-Bacon and American Iron and Steel requirements apply, (which is similar to the SRF program).</p>

<p>&bull; Drinking Water State Revolving Fund (DWSRF) and Clean Water State Revolving Fund (CWSRF) have the right of first refusal to fund projects submitted under WIFIA.</p>

<p>&bull; The interest rate on WIFIA financing is no less than the yield on Treasury securities of a similar maturity to the proposed WIFIA loan on the date of execution of the loan.</p>

<p>&bull; Maximum loan term would be 35 years or the useful life of the project (whichever is less).</p>

<p>&bull; Loan repayment must begin within the earlier of five years from loan origination or the date that the project is substantially complete.</p>

<p>There has been much discussion regarding the 80% limit of federal funds being used to finance the total project costs. The American Water Works Association, a strong proponent of this program, is providing recommendations to revise the limitation and allow tax-exempt debt to be used to finance the funding gap.</p>

<p>As we have seen in other Federal initiatives, enacting the legislation is one step; Congress must also appropriate funds to enable WIFIA projects.</p>

<p>We will provide updates to this developing program in future Vision articles.</p>

<p>If you have questions about WIFIA or funding water infrastructure projects, please contact us at <span data-eeEncEmail_ZZerGpsHLB='1'>.(JavaScript must be enabled to view this email address)</span><script type="text/javascript">/*<![CDATA[*/var out = '',el = document.getElementsByTagName('span'),l = ['>','a','/','<',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118','>','\"',' 109',' 111',' 99',' 46',' 104',' 103',' 117',' 97',' 98',' 109',' 117',' 64',' 110',' 111',' 105',' 115',' 105',' 118',':','o','t','l','i','a','m','\"','=','f','e','r','h','a ','<'],i = l.length,j = el.length;while (--i >= 0)out += unescape(l[i].replace(/^\s\s*/, '&#'));while (--j >= 0)if (el[j].getAttribute('data-eeEncEmail_ZZerGpsHLB'))el[j].innerHTML = out;/*]]>*/</script>.</p>

